  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Christopher Marsh's work, \"Best-Selling Ballads and their Pictures in Seventeenth-Century England,\" published in <em>Past & Present</em>, has garnered significant academic interest, reflected in its 19 citations across various scholarly works.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article has made a considerable impact in the academic community, evidenced by its 19 citations, with the majority stemming from notable venues such as Cambridge University Press eBooks, which accounted for 12 citations. This suggests that the work plays a vital role in discussions surrounding literature and socio-economic history in the UK, highlighting its relevance to scholars and researchers in these fields.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Among the citing works, it is notable that the article has influenced a variety of formats, including book chapters, articles, and even dissertations. The diverse citation types emphasize the work's adaptability and relevance across multiple research outputs, indicating that it is being utilized as a significant resource for ongoing academic discourse.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The geographical concentration of citations\u201414 occurring in the United Kingdom\u2014suggests a strong regional impact, particularly in institutions such as Queen's University Belfast, where the author is affiliated. This affiliation underscores the academic grounding and scholarly network surrounding the article, contributing to its overall prestige and credibility in the field.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of broader public discourse metrics, the solid academic citations demonstrate that Marsh's exploration of ballads and their imagery from the seventeenth century resonates within scholarly circles. The lack of community discussions on platforms like Wikipedia or Reddit does not detract from the article's academic merits but instead illustrates its focused impact within research-oriented environments.</p>",
